In mathematics, the '''Chihara–Ismail polynomials''' are a family of [[orthogonal polynomials]] introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Chihara|author1-link=Theodore Seio Chihara|last2=Ismail|author2-link=Mourad Ismail|year=1982}}, generalizing the '''van Doorn polynomials''' introduced by {{harvtxt|van Doorn|1981}} and the [[Karlin–McGregor polynomials]]. They have a rather unusual [[Measure (mathematics)|measure]], which is [[Discrete measure|discrete]] except for a single [[limit point]] at 0 with jump 0, and is non-symmetric, but whose support has an infinite number of both positive and negative points.

