In [[mathematics]], a '''Barnes zeta function''' is a generalization of the [[Riemann zeta function]] introduced by {{harvs|txt|authorlink=E. W. Barnes|first=E. W. |last=Barnes|year=1901}}. It is further generalized by the [[Shintani zeta function]].

==Definition==
The Barnes zeta function is defined by

: <math>\zeta_N(s,w\mid a_1,\ldots,a_N)=\sum_{n_1,\dots,n_N\ge 0}\frac{1}{(w+n_1a_1+\cdots+n_Na_N)^s}</math>
where ''w'' and ''a''<sub>''j''</sub> have positive real part and ''s'' has real part greater than&nbsp;''N''.

It has a [[meromorphic continuation]] to all complex ''s'', whose only [[Mathematical singularity|singularities]] are simple poles at ''s'' = 1, 2, ..., ''N''.  For ''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''w''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''a''<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 it is the Riemann zeta function.

